# Accessibility

Accessibility is a core quality requirement.

Every feature should be usable by as many people as possible without requiring separate implementations.

---

# Semantic HTML

Always prefer semantic HTML.

Use:

- header
- main
- nav
- section
- article
- footer
- button
- form
- label

Avoid replacing semantic elements with generic divs unless necessary.

---

# Keyboard Navigation

All interactive elements must be reachable using the keyboard.

Users should be able to:

- Tab through controls
- Activate buttons using Enter or Space
- Close dialogs using Escape when appropriate

Do not create keyboard traps.

---

# Focus States

Interactive elements must have visible focus indicators.

Never remove focus outlines without providing an accessible alternative.

Focus should always remain visible.

---

# Forms

Every form control must have:

- A visible label
- Appropriate placeholder text when helpful
- Validation feedback
- Helpful error messages

Errors should explain how users can resolve the issue.

Do not rely solely on color to communicate errors.

---

# Images

Every meaningful image must include descriptive alt text.

Decorative images should use:

alt=""

Do not leave alt text undefined.

---

# Buttons

Buttons should clearly describe their action.

Prefer:

"Submit RSVP"

Instead of:

"Click Here"

Avoid ambiguous labels.

---

# Links

Link text should describe the destination.

Avoid:

"Read More"

Prefer:

"View Wedding Timeline"

---

# Color Contrast

Maintain sufficient contrast between text and background.

Never rely on color alone to communicate meaning.

---

# Motion

Respect the user's reduced motion preference.

Animations should:

- Enhance the experience
- Never block interaction
- Never trigger unexpected movement

Provide reduced-motion alternatives where applicable.

---

# Responsive Accessibility

Ensure usability across:

- Mobile
- Tablet
- Desktop

Touch targets should be comfortably tappable.

Avoid placing interactive elements too close together.

---

# Screen Readers

Use accessible names for interactive elements.

When appropriate, provide:

- aria-label
- aria-labelledby
- aria-describedby

Only use ARIA when native HTML semantics are insufficient.

Prefer native HTML whenever possible.

---

# Loading States

Communicate loading clearly.

Disable actions that cannot be performed during loading.

Avoid layouts that shift unexpectedly.

---

# Error Handling

Error messages should:

- Explain what happened
- Explain how to fix it
- Be understandable by non-technical users

Never expose internal implementation details.

---

# Testing Checklist

Before completing UI work, verify:

- Keyboard navigation works.
- Focus is always visible.
- Forms have labels.
- Images have appropriate alt text.
- Color contrast is sufficient.
- Interactive elements are reachable.
- Reduced motion is respected.
- Responsive layouts remain usable.

Accessibility issues should be resolved before considering a feature complete.